Here's a minimal API endpoint that accepts multiple images plus a description field via `multipart/form-data`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Raise the max request body size to 50 MB
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 50 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (
    IFormFileCollection files,   // bound from all file parts
    HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Read the text field from the form
    var description = request.Form["description"].ToString();

    if (files.Count == 0)
        return Results.BadRequest("No files uploaded.");

    var saved = new List<string>();

    foreach (var file in files)
    {
        // Validate content type
        if (!file.ContentType.StartsWith("image/"))
            return Results.BadRequest($"'{file.FileName}' is not an image.");

        var destPath = Path.Combine("uploads", file.FileName);
        Directory.CreateDirectory("uploads");

        await using var stream = File.Create(destPath);
        await file.CopyToAsync(stream);
        saved.Add(file.FileName);
    }

    return Results.Ok(new { description, uploadedFiles = saved });
})
.DisableAntiforgery()   // required for form POSTs without a token
.Accepts<IFormFileCollection>("multipart/form-data");

app.Run();
```

**Key points:**

- **Size limit** — `MaxRequestBodySize` on Kestrel controls the cap. If you're behind IIS/Nginx you need to configure those separately too.
- **`IFormFileCollection`** — binds every `<input type="file">` part automatically.
- **Text fields** — accessed via `request.Form["description"]` since minimal APIs don't model-bind mixed form + file payloads into a single object.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** — needed in .NET 8+ because antiforgery is on by default for form endpoints.

**Test with `curl`:**

```bash
curl -X POST http://localhost:5000/upload \
  -F "files=@photo1.jpg" \
  -F "files=@photo2.png" \
  -F "description=Vacation photos"
```
